        id: 'faqs',
        heading: `Frequently Asked Questions About CASS for Businesses`,
        content: `To further clarify how the **Current Account Switch Service** operates for businesses, here are detailed answers to some of the most commonly asked questions by business owners.

**Will switching affect my business credit score?**

Opening a new bank account involves a credit check by the new provider, which can leave a hard footprint on your business credit report. However, simply using the **Current Account Switch Service** does not inherently damage your credit score.

In fact, moving to an account that better suits your financial situation, offers better credit facilities, or reduces your fees could be highly beneficial for your business's financial health in the long run.

**Can I choose my switch date?**

Yes, you have the flexibility to choose the exact date your switch completes, provided it is at least seven working days after your new account is officially opened and is not a weekend or a public bank holiday.

This allows you to select a date that minimizes disruption, such as a quiet period in your billing cycle or immediately after your monthly payroll has been processed.

**What happens to my old bank account?**

As a mandatory part of the **CASS** process, your old business bank account will be automatically closed on your switch date.

This ensures that you do not accidentally incur maintenance fees on an inactive account and helps keep your financial records clean and organized. It also prevents any confusion regarding where your funds are held.

**What if I change my mind?**

If you change your mind about switching, you can cancel the process up to seven working days before your agreed switch date.

Once you are within the seven-day window, the process is locked in and cannot be stopped, as the automated systems will have already begun transferring your data and payment mandates.`
